==English==
===Etymology===
From Old English [[entaile]] carving from Old French [[entaille]], French, an incision, from [[entailler]] to cut away; prefix en-  Latin + tailler to cut; late Latin feudum talliatum a fee entailed, i. e., curtailed or limited. 

===Pronunciation===
*{{audio|en-us-entail.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
'''entail'''
#That which is entailed. Hence: 
#:An [[estate]] in fee entailed, or [[limited]] in descent to a particular [[class]] of [[issue]]. 
#:The [[rule]] by which the [[descent]] is [[fixed]].
#::''"A power of breaking the ancient entails, and of alienating their estates."'' &mdash; Hume.
#(''obsolete'') Delicately [[carved]] [[ornamental]] work; [[intaglio]]. 
#:''"A work of rich entail."'' &mdash; Spenser.


===Transitive verb===
'''entail'''
#To [[imply]] or [[require]].
#:''This activity will '''entail''' careful attention to detail.''
#To [[settle]] or [[fix]] [[inalienably]] on a person or thing, or on a person and his descendants or a certain line of [[descendants]]; -- said especially of an estate; to [[bestow]] as an [[heritage]].
#:''"Allowing them to entail their estates."''&mdash; Hume.
#:''"I here entail The crown to thee and to thine heirs forever."'' &mdash; Shakespeare
#(''obsolete'') To appoint hereditary possessor. [Obs.]
#:''"To entail him and his heirs unto the crown."''&mdash; Shakespeare
#(''obsolete'') To cut or carve in a ornamental way. [Obs.]
#:''"Entailed with curious antics."'' &mdash; Spenser.

